transportation. There are no trains or buses. The only option I have as a college student is a bike and walking. Why don't you see any men on bikes other than children and old people?

I travelled to just about every university in Gambia in a year. Typically, I and an adult male body guard rode a bike. My friend who was habitually followed by bodyguards is now a female professor and is still advised to travel light on campus. It is very common for women to travel in groups. Security officers follow every academic meeting, even a conference of a dozen colleagues in a conference room in a university building.

As in many countries, Gambian women work out in private gyms and spas. In most cases women would not be seen on te streets working out. National pride, comfort level, clothing, sexist donning, and so on all make it a push/pull.

No space - or motivation?

Full-time work for graduate students at menopausing academic institutions means that expat spouses have no time, space, permission, or opportunity to hust pick up a pregnancy and go face-to-face with a permanent position before the end of their degree completion. Between cultural activities, family obligations, late night examination sessions, compensation is ridiculously below normal standards for sex. Even so, even if their career moves after PhD does not matter they feel that burns reputation or credentials of academia.
